+sub_section( 'Headings Hierarchy' )

	+video( 'https://learn.wordpress.org/tutorial/using-headings-for-accessibility-and-seo/' ) How to use headings for accessibility and SEO

	+video( 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_xecSWaqiUw' ) Alternative video about headings hierarchy

	p To comply with accessibility guidelines, the theme follows this headings structure:

	dl
		dt Max one <code>h1</code> on any given page
		dd
			p Theme outputs only one first-level heading (HTML tag <code>&lt;h1></code>) on each page. This is reserved for a page main title.

			+important( 'Exceptions in templates', 'h4' )
				p Read more about exception from this rule applied with certain <a href="#page-templates">templates</a>. For example, you can remove the <code>h1</code> title altogether and create your own custom one in a page content.

		if true !== config.compatibility.fse
			dt Site title heading
			dd
				block accessibility/headings/site_title
					p Site title (logo) is rendered as <code>h1</code> only on homepage with blog display. On other pages (including the <a href="#pages">static home page</a>) the <code>h1</code> tag is reserved for the actual page main title.

		dt Hierarchy
		dd
			p Theme follows the best practice by hierarchically organizing heading levels, not skipping any of them. For example, <code>h3</code> headings can be found only in a section titled with level <code>h2</code> (and not <code>h1</code>). <strong>You should do the same when building your site content</strong> too.

			+tip( 'Test it out!', 'h4' )
				p In case you would like to test a page headings hierarchy, there is a great browser extension for this called <a href="https://github.com/dzc34/headingsMap"><strong>HeadingsMap</strong></a>.
